SIMPLE: reset
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reset
<hw>Re*set"</hw></mhw> <pr>(r?-s?t")</pr>,
<pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set again; <as>as, to
<ex>reset</ex> type; to <ex>reset</ex> copy; to <ex>reset</ex> a
diamond</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To set (an instrument) back to an initial position
after it has changed; of instruments and dials; <as>as, he
<ex>reset</ex> the timer to ten minutes started again</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> reset, set to zero.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reset</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Reset
<hw>Re"set</hw> <pr>(r?"s?t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of resetting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>That which is reset; matter set
up again.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reset</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Reset
<hw>Re*set"</hw> <pr>(r?-s?t")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>recete</ets>, <ets>recepte</ets>, a receiving. Cf.
<er>Receipt</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>The receiving of
stolen goods, or harboring an outlaw.</def>
<rj><au>Jamieson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reset</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Reset
<hw>Re*set"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>To harbor
or secrete; to hide, as stolen goods or a criminal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We shall see if an English hound is to harbor and <qex>reset</qex>
the Southrons here.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Resetter</ent>⟦br⟧
